Why are you being a dick? He explained the difference accurately - JS compares objects as individual objects. Arrays are objects. The other languages you cited do not work that way.<p>Here&#x27;s another example:<p><pre><code>    4 == 4 // true
    a = new Number(4);
    b = new Number(4);
    a == b // false
    a == a // true
    a.valueOf() // 4
    b.valueOf() // 4
    a.valueOf() == b.valueOf() // true
</code></pre>
And if this isn&#x27;t clear yet:<p><pre><code>    a = {}
    b = {}
    a == a // true
    a == b // false</code></pre>
